n order to ensure order and stability. Suggesting that all concepts of modern political thought are secularized theological concepts, Schmitt concludes Political Theology with a critique of liberalism and its attempt to depoliticize political thought by avoiding fundamental political decisions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aPolitical science. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  asovereignty, political philosophy, weimar republic, carl schmitt, social order, stability, secularism, liberalism, revolution, donoso cortes, bonald, de maistre, government, power, authority, coup, regime change, security, freedom, nazi, germany, politics, legal normativism, liberal democracy, religion, theology, monarchy, history, nonfiction.1 aSchwab, George, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchwab, George, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aStrong, Tracy B.1 aStrong, Tracy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226738901423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226738901/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles